“As a DevOps Engineer, my typical day starts by checking the health of our production and staging environments using CloudWatch and Grafana dashboards. I make sure all our EC2 instances, EKS clusters, and Jenkins jobs are running fine and that there are no active alerts.

After that, I attend the daily stand-up with developers and QA to discuss any ongoing deployments or blockers. Once that’s done, I usually review Jenkins pipelines — making sure builds and deployments are successful. If there are failed jobs, I troubleshoot the issue,
fix pipeline scripts, or modify the build stages if needed.

A big part of my work involves managing infrastructure using Terraform and Ansible. I write and update Terraform modules for provisioning AWS resources like EC2, S3, IAM, and EKS. For configuration management, I use Ansible to automate setup tasks across multiple servers.

I also work closely with Docker and Kubernetes — building container images, pushing them to ECR, and deploying them to our EKS clusters using Helm charts. During the day, I monitor logs through CloudWatch or ELK and handle any alerts or incidents that come up, 
performing root cause analysis when required.

Towards the end of the day, I usually work on optimizing CI/CD processes, automating repetitive manual steps, and updating documentation in Confluence or Jira. Overall, my focus is on keeping deployments smooth, infrastructure stable, and improving automation across our environments.” 
 


“In our CI/CD setup, the process starts when developers push code changes to GitHub. A webhook automatically triggers Jenkins, which pulls the latest code and initiates the build process.
During the build stage, we run unit tests, static code analysis, and security scans using tools like SonarQube to maintain code quality and compliance. Once the build passes, Jenkins creates a Docker image, tags it with the build number and commit ID, 
and pushes it to Amazon ECR for version control.
In the deployment phase, Jenkins triggers a Helm release to update our Kubernetes workloads running on Amazon EKS. We use a rolling update strategy to ensure zero downtime, and maintain Helm value files for environment-specific configurations.
Post-deployment, Jenkins runs smoke tests and health checks to verify that the services are functioning correctly. If any issues are detected, Jenkins automatically triggers a rollback to the previous stable version using Helm’s revision history.
Notifications for every build and deployment status are integrated with Slack and email, so the entire team stays informed. We also use CloudWatch and Grafana for continuous monitoring and alerting to ensure system stability.
This CI/CD pipeline is fully automated and version-controlled, helping us deliver faster, more reliable, and consistent deployments across all environments.”

